segments.text: We publish booklets and we give them information in closing and we visit with all the landscape architects and architectural, I mean, landscape firms that operate in the woodlands to try to get them to think about this natural environment and saving trees.
So that's an ongoing process.
Yeah, every year we have something called Arbor Day and we've given away, how many of them?
330,000 seedlings and small trees.
And people stand in line to get those trees and they take them home and plant them in the yard.
And we just got together in the Wildflower Festival.
Wildflowers are deeply a part of the image of the woodlands.
Lady Bird Johnson has been here for several seminars.
She's deeply involved in wildflowers.
And Texas wildflowers are something we plant and cultivate every year and have a very well-defined program to propagate those.
At what point following 86 did you feel like you were rounding the hump, let's say, of the financial?
You may not have felt that way yet.
I guess we're still working on it.
Statistically, the third quarter of 1987 is when the Houston economy started rebounding.
I think we gained 12,000 jobs in Houston in the third quarter of 1987 after having lost 200,000.
That was the first time you could see it coming back.
In 1988, I think we gained maybe 30,000 jobs at about that level, maybe 40,000 jobs in 1989.
According to a study done by Barton Smith at the University of Houston, you probably know, Houston is now about 60% energy dependent, where it was 80% energy dependent.
And the strengths are, you know, the port of Houston, it's number one in the nation in terms of export tonnage.
And most of that is not petroleum related.
It's grain and foodstuffs and things like that.
The NASA Space Center, of course, has come back strongly during the downturn.
During that downturn, we were blessed, too, with the largest highway construction program ever undertaken in this region.
More than a billion dollars a year was spent on highway construction in the Houston region, which exceeded any other state in the nation except California for a five-year period of time.
And, of course, the tremendous growth and expansion of the Texas Medical Center
The $5 billion expansion program underway out there and it's still ongoing.
It really helped the Houston economy.
Compact Computer came into being.
It didn't exist in 1982.
And that's one of the major companies in this country.
And it's located 20 miles away.
The biotechnology industry and startup companies that have come out of that.
Dr. Dominic Lamb, you'll enjoy that interview.
He's a very interesting, intelligent, bright, energetic person.
You'll get a lot from Dr. Lamb.
There was another matter I was going to mention.
Maybe I'll come back to him in a moment.
By 88, things are... Yeah, by 88, you can see things moving in the right direction.
89 was a good year.
This year, we'll have a record year in home sales.
So far, we've sold almost $120 billion worth of home sales, $120 million worth of home sales.
$120 million worth of new homes this year.
Oh, no, the Barton Smith study.
We had him conduct a study to determine what is the impact of the Woodlands on the economy of Montgomery County.
In the early days, the Woodlands was not well accepted by Montgomery County.
There's a great deal of suspicion and doubt and uncertainty.
Even hostility from the commissioners.
Hostility.
And there is still some of that, but it's beginning to wane, and obviously it's not so bad.
But the interesting thing about that study is that now the Woodlands...
It constitutes 17% of the tax base in the county.
It is the biggest single taxpaying entity in the county today.
At one time, the Conroe oil field was the dominant economic generator for taxes in the county.
And now the Woodlands exceeds, and when I say the Woodlands, I mean all the homes, all the development.
Collectively.
The Woodlands pays more taxes than the Conroe oil field pays to support schools and the county government.
We also now constitute about 16% of the voting population in the county.
The community is predominantly Republican, predominantly conservative, and it's changed the shape of politics within the county.
When I moved here 20 something years ago in Montgomery County, you could not find anyone who would profess to be a Republican.
except Dr. Wally Wilkerson, who was part of the Republican Party.
Today, you can't find anybody who agrees that they're a Democrat.
Even the local officeholders who originally were elected as Democrats have now changed to the Republican Party for fear of being defeated.
The Woodlands has done, I think, a number of positive things for the county.
It's helped create economic growth.
It's helped create jobs.
It's provided, I think, the numbers, 25% of the...
retail sales are generated by people who live in the Woodlands.
That's not 25% of retail sales occurring in the Woodlands, but the population of the Woodlands generates 25% of the retail sales.
Has this study been published?
I'll give you a copy of it.
I think we'd like that.
Jack, could you see it?
It's interesting reading.
I got Dr. Smith to do it, so it would be objective.
We could do it, but that would not be held to be fairly objective.
Yeah, credibility would be questioned.
But this will give you some good background information from a third-party source.
It's got a good executive summary, and then he kind of gets involved in the science of evaluating demographics and economic evaluation.
the executive summary makes more exciting reading than the methodology.

So, what do you think now, so we're in, you and you now, are in a position of potential expansion, let's say, on the conditions of potentially good, but... Well, you know, we've got the same over in the Gulf, and we've got oil prices that...
It went down $5 a barrel yesterday, and I don't know what they've done today.
And there is a devastating financial condition for financing real estate nationally.
And while the market is good in the Houston region, financial institutions don't look favorably upon real estate financing.
So I think it's going to have some detrimental effect on Houston, even though we're doing much better than the nation as a whole.
We still look to the money-centered banks for a lot of financing.
And I don't think that it's going to be as generous as we would like for it to be.
But so far, we've spent $2 billion in the woods total.
$2 billion has been invested by all parties in the woods.
A billion dollars of that is in residential homes owned by third parties.
The rest of it's in schools and churches
office buildings and research facilities and land development and those kinds of things.
Upon completion, total investment in the woodlands will be about $12 billion by all parties.
And the population will be somewhere around 150,000 people.
And we anticipate having about 80,000 jobs, permanent jobs.
Someone asked, when are you going to finish developing the woodlands?

and the very clear answer to that we never will because no city is ever complete i don't think he's ever driven through any city in this country where you could say they have finished i mean there will always be redevelopment the reconstruction of buildings replacement of housing but essentially most of the development will will have occurred by the year 2027
We have a very definite plan year by year, unit by unit.
You asked about the strategy for developing it.
We have an economic model that we update annually that looks forward and takes into account changes since we last did it.
Is that in-house?
Is that done in-house?
We do it with some outside consulting help, but it's an in-house document that we produce our own.
planning purposes.
And we don't publish that.
Do you see this kind of expansion of population growth and so forth as being a threat or a great difficulty in continuing to manage the environment and the quality of life type situation?
Or do you feel quite comfortable that can be accommodated?
I think it can be accomplished, but it's becoming more complicated.
You know, I think the 1990s is going to be the decade of the environment.
We see things like

concerned about hazardous waste endangered species the wetlands the Clean Air Act all of those things are going to come to bear and frankly I don't think in the future you're going to see very many large-scale communities like the woodlands undertaken in the future for those very reasons there's so much uncertainty over the life span of developing a community like this that
You deal with a lot of uncertainties, a lot of risk involved.
You have so much front-end investment that you have to recoup out of the assumption of later development.
Q And, Shane, are there any more government initiatives in that direction that you would like to see?
THE PRESIDENT.
No, I don't think you probably will.
I think the government involvement should be one of providing incentives and not providing roadblocks.
Actually, some people look at the Woodlands as a government-sponsored community.
We borrowed $50 million to start the development of the Woodlands, but we're paying that back.
That was a loan.
That was not a gift from heaven.
It was a little lower interest rate, but when you add to it all the administrative costs of monitoring that for the government and reporting and the hassle you go through, I'm not sure it was a
A good bargain.
George Mitchell will tell you it was a tremendous bargain.
But I lived over here working on those reports that had to go in.
And there was a cost attached to that.
But I think the environment is going to be a great challenge in the future.
We, I think, tried to address it very well.
And I think we've done a pretty good job of it.
But I think there are going to be more and more rules and regulations promulgated without a clear understanding of the impact
It's going to cause uncertainties and delays.
And the delays are the money.
And when you get one of these started, you really need to move along with it.
You can't have periods of time when you do nothing.
What projects are you really devoting most of your time to right now?
Or is there any kind of, any kind of affinity like that in what I'm doing?
I'm pretty well involved in all the projects that are going on.
And it's hard in a community like this to separate it into a series of projects.
They're all interrelated.
Right now, this week, we have the formal opening of a new 18-hole golf course designed by Arnold Palmer.
And we are expanding the country club in a large amount.
What is that opening?
It's on the 30th.
You're invited.
Thank you, sir.
Come at 11 o'clock.

But right now, after being here 15 years, a number of our facilities are 15 years old, and we have had an ongoing refurbishing program, but right now it's a little more intensive than it has been in the past.
We've renovated the conference center, updated the guest rooms, enlarging the country club, separating the conference center from the country club, so there are two separate entities over there.
We're enlarging the golf facilities because the membership has grown tremendously.
We're engaged in, continually engaged in this economic development program and encouraging businesses to locate here.
And the main thrust of Madigan would be, right now, is in the medical area, in the, say, the youth, I'm using the umbrella of the Youth and Advanced Research area.
And also well-established companies looking for a home.
For example, we have the Products Testing Laboratory for Penzol here, a well-established company.
Betts Process Chemical has a major operation here.
Up in the Trade Center, you may or may not have seen it, it's a rail-serve trade center and major distribution centers there owned by Michelin Tire, Kraft Food, Eckerd Drug,
The distribution outlet for McDonald's, as well as Burger King are there.
Are you continuing that expansion?
Yeah.
As a matter of fact, most of our buildings are completely full there.
We have an ongoing program to enhance and improve the mobility of the region through the encouragement of improving highways.
We've created here in the Woodlands, and I think this is kind of unique, we've created a commuter van system.
and also commuter bus parking ride system.
We're outside the service area of the Houston Metro, so they could not bring buses into the woodlands.
So we worked through the county and got a federal grant, and we built a parking ride lot, and we financed the buses.
It's now being operated by Brazos Transit Authority, which is located in Bryan, I believe.
They do a good job.
Yeah, they do a good job here, too.
So we've been able to take, you know, four, five, six hundred cars off the highway by creating alternative systems for transportation.
Is there no internal transportation?
Would you anticipate ever having to do something like that?
Well, we're setting aside right-of-ways and the provision for that to occur.
There's no defined plan to make it happen currently.
Most of those that have been attempted have failed.
Without some heavy subsidy, it's hard to...
Even up to Brian, I don't know.
I was wondering about rail service.
Do you need to keep it there?
Do you think you had a monorail or anything like that in the Houston-Dallas connection?
Well, that's always a possibility, and part of the dream that we have is there's a plan for this high-speed rail from Dallas to Houston and to San Antonio.
And there are a couple of alternate routes for that.
Both are to the west of the Woodlands.
They would not come through the Woodlands.
So I don't think we'd be exposed to that opportunity, but we do have a rail system here at the front door.
And there's great debate in the city of Houston, as you know right now, about heavy rail, whether or not to have it, and if so, where, and who pays for it.
If, as you commented, the 90s become the decade of the environmental movement, highway building, if it's pursued logically, would diminish, I would think.
Go ahead.
Alternative, as you suggested, alternative transport modes would have to then
Yeah, I think you're going to see those pressures.
I think you're exactly right.
With respect to the specific question about rail, I don't think that's in the immediate 10-year horizon just because of cost and time to build it, who owns it and how it operates.
There are a lot of questions that need to be answered about rail before it's implemented anywhere in the Houston region, I think.
Great debate about that thing.
What about recreation as an economic investment?
That's a good question.
That's a good question.
Back when I got started in the real estate development business, developers typically built golf courses to help sell land and then hope they didn't lose too much money and usually gave it away to

The members, if they would take it or sell it to someone for a small number of dollars, Club Corporation of America became wealthy by taking over clubs that developers didn't want, didn't know how to run, or that members couldn't operate.
Today, that's changed.
Golf is a business, and it's a profitable business.
And we have, we just finished a study looking at golf meets in the woodlands.
Right now, we have four 18-hole golf courses.
One of them is a tournament players course, which is in fact a day-to-day course.
You don't have to be a member to play.
We have one course for the conferees who visit the conference center for recreational purposes.
And we have two 18-hole courses set aside for country club membership.
And we had the firm by the name of Real Estate Research Associates of California do a
comprehensive study course looking at the total golf needs and demands throughout the life of the Woodlands.
And in total we need 10 golf courses in the Woodlands, 10 18-hole golf courses.
But we need six more than we have today.
And that would be a combination of a second tournament players course, which we have the right to build, a 36-hole daily feed course, a public course,
for those who cannot afford or choose not to belong to a country club.
And then a more exclusive country club than the one we have today, a higher-end club, maybe an equity club where the members would own that.
We're combining that now with our land planning for the remaining portions of the woodlands to make sure we set aside enough land in the right place to accommodate those golfing needs.
Is the skiing operation under your surveillance also?
Is it all the ski lines or skiing lifts in Colorado?
Yeah.
We've got all the real estate falls under- Within the corporation?
Yeah.
We've got two parcels of land in Colorado, one between Aspen and Snowmass, and one at Simbo Springs.
The regulatory environment up there is a morass.
You have the Forest Service.
Yeah, dealing with everybody.
Forest Service is the one who grants permits, but you deal with everyone who chooses to deal with you.
But in the area between Aspen and Snowmass, we have developed about 800 acres of land and have sold lots to individuals who have built homes.
And that's in the very beautiful Owl Creek Valley that extends the entire distance from the town of Aspen to the town of Snowman.
And in Steamboat Springs, we have 3,000 acres of land that we own jointly with a third party.
And there we're actively trying to get a permit to build a ski mountain.
And that one will take on a different character from what we have in Aspen.
has been very low density.
The only thing that, you know, recreation can tie in nicely with your quality of life and with the impact on your medical care, atmosphere, and even with the environment.
The jogging path.
Yeah.
You asked about other recreational things here in the Woodlands, and you mentioned jogging paths.
That's probably the single most popular recreational amenity we have.
We have 53 miles of pathway.
And it's off the
$20 a foot to build that.
Is that your cost?
$10,000 a month.
$10,000 a month.
Forget the number.
$5 to $10 million invested in this pathway.
I mean, that's tremendous investment in a recreational facility.
But it's used by everybody.
Kids on bicycles, people out for exercise.
people both jogging and riding bicycles and actually commuting in some cases from home to school and from home to shopping.
We've got some of the retirement communities located close to the shopping center and you see people in wheelchairs walking down and moving down the pathway to go to the grocery store.
So it's kind of a nice feel to it.
We have a swimming athletic center which is

olympic quality in terms of its facility as a matter of fact olympic tryouts are held there and we're in the process of enlarging and upgrading that currently i think in uh summary i really take up how much time you wanted to give us but um i still got a couple questions okay you go ahead well one of the things which you started and we got distracted away from you mentioned some of the things that in the future
not that they worry, but the things you're planning to do.
The other side of that coin is, what are the future incentives or the initiatives that you perceive?
Are there future initiatives?
Is it going to be business as usual, or are there other initiatives that the Woodlands is going to develop in the next two, three decades?
Well, yeah, there are very specific things that we need to develop in the next several decades.
One is Town Center.
Town Center is
well defined on paper, still defined if you try to find it.
But it will include about 17 million square feet of office space, which is equivalent to the downtown of probably Cincinnati, if you measure it in square footage.
But it will include a regional shopping mall, and it will be the urbanized center for Northeastern.
Not only the urbanized center for Woodlands, but we look at that as a focal point for business in Northeastern.
The termination of the Hardy Toll Road is on I-45.
It's the intersection of some major east-west roadways under design and partially under construction, and it will be the center of population for more than a million people.
So we look at that as a big item on our agenda for the next 10 to 15 years.
We look at the research forest only at its beginning stages right now, and we would hope

we would have 15,000, 20,000 jobs in the research forest over the next 20 years, and in fact do things like have been done in the research triangle of North Carolina or around the Stanford and the Silicon Valley or Route 128 in Boston.
So that's a long-term goal and objective.
We work on it every day, and we try not to lose sense of direction of where we're trying to get to and be discouraged if we haven't gotten there as quickly as we'd like.
Those are two very big elements.

Beyond that, the continuation of a quality residential program on the remaining lands in the woodlands that continues to provide housing opportunities for the secretary and the clerk and the grocery store as well as the chairman of the board.
All done in a tasteful way.
Neighborhoods that are close together.
So you get this social intermixing of it.

school level anyway other schools where you don't have an elitist side of town and a poor side of town so that's an objective that we had from the beginning and we still pursue we have a couple of major lakes we'd like to build in the woodlands for recreational purposes and that's going to take some regulatory approval governmental health and things like that but that's part of the mission that we
look at it as being important to us.
Let me answer a couple of specific questions.
My brother's a city manager in Las Vegas.
He's been doing that for more than a dozen years.
I called him several months ago, or actually a better part of a year ago, when we first started kicking around with the tickets.
Well, over the years I've talked to them, I'm completely at sea when it comes to the niceties or the crudities, however you want to look at it, of running a community.
Both definitions are right.
You mentioned that the Woodlands is non-incorporated.
That's right.
Will it be?
Well, let me give you the legal side and then maybe the practical side, a little background.
Right now we have a community association.
We were formed when the Woodlands was created.
and is supported financially by assessments applied against all the properties that have been developed in the area.
And it has about a $6 million budget now.

And it provides all the municipal services that the city would provide, including the fire department, the collection of garbage, the street escape maintenance, neighborhood watch programs, emergency medical services, street lights, mowing grass, maintaining the parks and pathways.
does everything the city would do.
And the outlook is for that mechanism to continue until one of two things happens.
The woodlands become separately incorporated in the city, or it's incorporated into the corporate boundaries of the city of Houston.
And under current state law, the woodlands is in the extraterritorial jurisdiction of the city of Houston.

the city of houston has the right and authority to annex the woodlands anytime it would like to do that as a practical matter i don't think they will for another year for a couple reasons one we're not contiguous to the existing boundaries of the city of houston and they would have to step over a lot of the land that would not be in their corporate boundaries and two they're not going to annex the woodlands as long as there's a
significant debt existing in the municipal utility districts that have been created to provide utilities.
The way to let that is to pay down.
I would think that over the next 20 years, unless state law changes, that Woodlands will become part of the community.
Are you, is that part, is that an assumption built into your strategic plan?
Yes.
Okay.
I'll go on to say, too, that if you took a vote in the Woodlands today, there'd probably be 90% of the people who would choose not to be in the city of Houston and maybe 10% who would.
So it would not necessarily be a popular decision.
But when you think about it on a regional basis and you step aside from the selfish, what's best for me, question,

Cities up in the northeastern part of the country and other parts of the country have been choked, small incorporated cities surrounding them, people, productive people moving out of the inner city, living and paying taxes in these small incorporated areas.
And the central city has no tax base or declining tax base to provide social services, the airport, the library, the museum, the streets that lead to the jobs where people work.
And philosophically, George Mitchell felt that the city of Houston needed to have the ability to continue to annex land and grow as it could provide services for those areas.
So by contract, the Woodlands is included in ETJ.
It was not geographically situated to be included in ETJ, but by contract, it is now included in ETJ, the city of Houston.
Isn't that, I mean, a lot of what you said, you know, where you could go, well, one, does the community in fact know that?
Yes.
They do know that.
Isn't that then a potential source of some grievous conflict in the future?
Yes.
Which means, I mean, what's going to happen?
Well, right now the approach, and I think the realistic response is that

nothing is going to happen for a period of time the city of houston is not going to annex the woodland for a period of time you know likelihood if it's a sleeping dog that's going to wake up well it slept in a place called clear lake city until the residents there challenged the system and under state law an area can if it wants to separately incorporate
first has to ask the city in whose ETJ it resides to annex them.
And if the city refuses to do that, then they can unincorporate.
The Clear Lake City asked the question, and they were annexed into the city of Houston.
And that was not a pleasant set of circumstances.
It existed for a number of years.
As you look around Houston,
Every major large-scale community is an ETJ in the city of Houston.
It's not unique to the woodlands.
No, I know that.
So wherever you locate around the city of Houston, you're faced with the same issue.
So it's not a unique woodlands question.
It's a regional issue.
But the distinction is, I mean, forgive me, but the distinction is those communities, this is a corporation running a community.
You know, that isn't happening.
Kingwood is, too.
Oh, is it?
Mm-hmm.
Fair Lake City is, too.

Oh, because what I would... You know, at least it would be a nagging headache in the back of my skull that at some point, instead of animosity being turned toward the city of Houston or some other place, that I'm going to catch it in my lap, you know.
Well, under the community association that we have here, it's a representative form of government.
The residents elect...
representatives to serve on their behalf on the board of directors that addresses all of the services and charges for those services, the scope of delivering those services.
And in fact, in 1992, the residents will control that WCA board, the community association board, and the developer will no longer control that one.
So it's not that the corporation controls the community.
the residents will control the community.
You're in the middle of that transfer right now.
Yeah, right.
That was my second question.
We're in the transition.
That takes place in 1992, and we're trying to go through the discussion of trying to prepare the community for that happening.
And right now, frankly, there is some confusion.
It's a complicated issue, but most people don't think about it day to day.
It's not something they deal with.
And then when confronted with the notion that something's going to happen, the natural reaction is, if it's changing, I need to be concerned about it.
And then they try to learn quickly what they need to be concerned about.
And we're going through a very lengthy educational process now to make sure they don't misunderstand that we're the bad guys.
Sure.
That was my other question.
As the privatization of city management...
you know, what's your role?
How do you, you know, how will you continue to influence or affect the quality of life issues, the infrastructure that you've worked so hard to establish?
Well, we hope we put in place a framework with respect to those areas already developed that will last long after the development is on.
That was the, I don't like the word scheme, that was the concept.
to put in place a form of quasi-government.
Residents would run, control, operate, and take care of their own needs.
Our intent is not to be here forever.
It just probably seems that we will be.
We'll be here for a long time.
But in 1992, when this first community association control transfers to the residents,
A second community association will be formed to carry out the development mission on lands not yet developed.
So we will, in essence, control.
We'll have the capacity to control the undeveloped lands with respect to lands already developed the residents will control that.
So there's a transfer of control with respect to what's already been done.
In terms of residential development, you're about halfway where you've
No.
No, we've got 30,000 people live here, 150,000 or whatever percent that is.
But it's an accelerating phase.
If we don't have eight years of economic hardship, maybe we'll move along faster.
We're 16 years old and we've
been in the doldrums eight of those 16 years.
So I think our progress has been, I think, surprisingly good, considering the time that we've been here.
Well, I think you can see, whereas the rest of the country has been in relaxation now, you've still been pretty active.
Let me ask one last question, and then I'll shut up.
And you may find this impertinent, but it's something that I wondered about as I talked with Mr. Richmond, Mr. Brown, and now you.
What would happen?
to the Woodlands if George Mitchell died tomorrow?
Well, the Woodlands Corporation is a wholly owned subsidiary of a public corporation.
George, in fact, owns 62% of the stock of that corporation, but it is publicly held and will have an ongoing life should something unfortunate happen to Mr. Mitchell.
I'm not privy to how his estate would be managed.
I would not expect any great changes over the short term.
Over a longer period of time, I don't guess I would be capable of addressing that.
There's enough framework in the Woodlands, just talking about the Woodlands itself and the community of the Woodlands.
There's enough framework here already in place and enough initiatives in place, and it's
market vitality has been established to the point where I think it could have an ongoing life beyond Mr. Mitchell.
You feel that the strategic plans you've developed and the machinery of those are going to continue on regardless?
Yeah, there may be some modification to it, but I've come back to the earlier statements.
What we've tried to do is build fabric in the community that gives the community an ongoing life and set it in place.
It's an institution that has a life of its own.
And it will be a viable community.
You know, a town of 30,000 people is not a small town.
And it's got a lot of elements in it that are necessary to make it function, even if it's reading up others.
By 92, basically, the Woodlands Corporation would be another business located in the Woodlands.
Well, except that they'll still be developing.
Well, we're going to continue to develop.
In 1992, you won't be able to tell any difference visually if you drive in here.
And if you live here, you probably won't notice any difference either.
Legally, there'll be some changes that take place.
But I think with respect to the development concept, the quality of what we're doing, the pace at which we're doing it, the way it's financed,
It's a unique opportunity, a unique place.
It's nice to have a sense of pride in what you're doing.
I guess the most satisfying
things I can do is not sit here in the office, but occasionally on the weekend drive around and see what's happening.
I mean, it's kind of impressive when you get out and look at all the things that have happened.
And we get caught up in the fires like anyone else.
There's a crisis today or a crisis tomorrow, and we address that, and we like to think we always have a long-range vision, but in truth and in fact, you have daily things that you need to do.
And it's nice to
back away occasionally to reflect on what has happened and what can't happen.
And we've got a staff of people who have been here a long time.
That was my next question.
How do you work?
Do you have staff meetings regularly?
Yeah, we have staff meetings and planning meetings and meetings on special issues.
But we've got most of our employees have been with us 10, 15 years and been working together as a team for that period of time.
We don't have a lot of turnover.
You don't have to have quite as many meetings when people have been around that long.
Everyone knows what they need to do and what's expected of them.

But in managing this process, we have a staff meeting once a week where our key managers get together and talk about the issues and try to stay away from numbers and details and look at the big picture.
Then we have specific planning meetings
in the residential communities and also in the commercial and retail areas.
We have staff groups, like Jack provides advertising and VR services to the operating units.
Each operating unit doesn't have an advertising and VR person.
We have a centralized engineering and construction group.
We have a centralized land planning group.
You can have Dick Brown, apparently.
We have centralized legal, accounting, and other services.
And then we have essentially three operating groups.
